 speaks to how hard it is for highly tuned and highly scaled business model=
s like Search to extend to new areas. The big question about AI is if it is=
 close enough to Search that Google can fold it in to its current business =
model, or if the shift away from ten blue links ends up breaking the entire=
 thing.

The Complicity Framework
------------------------

This last section was actually written by a friend; he asked me to give it =
a once-over, and I thought it was worth including in Stratechery (with perm=
ission, of course), particularly in the context of yesterday=E2=80=99s Arti=
cle. In yesterday=E2=80=99s conclusion I suggested that the best approach f=
or Google and Meta was a personalized AI that was tuned using the same data=
 used for personalized advertising. This is another solution to some of the=
 same issues, particularly questions around =E2=80=9Csafety=E2=80=9D.

The AI safety debate is currently unproductive because its focus is on the =
wrong actor: AI. In fact, every AI interaction involves two actors: the AI =
and the human prompting the AI. The way to solve the =E2=80=9CAI safety deb=
ate=E2=80=9D is to render it moot by shifting perceived culpability away fr=
om AI to humans.

To illustrate the spectrum over which this shift occurs, consider the follo=
wing unpleasant example (chosen because it is politically neutral =E2=80=94=
 everyone hates it!): the creation of an image of a bunny rabbit being tort=
ured.

*Scenario 1: A user creates the image in MS Paint or Adobe Photoshop by han=
d*

No one would blame Microsoft or Adobe if a user spent hours creating our un=
fortunate picture using MS Paint or Photoshop. The perceived culpability wo=
uld be completely with the artist.

*Scenario 2: A user generates a bunny rabbit using AI and then depicts tort=
ure in MS Paint or Adobe Photoshop by hand*

This picture takes much less time, and is probably of higher quality: the u=
ser might first ask AI to draw a bunny with realistic fur and features; the=
n the user asks AI to create a realistic pair of pincers. After that the ar=
tist uses Photoshop to combine the two images to depict torture.

This image is almost entirely AI generated, and yet I suspect there would b=
e no AI safety issue: this scenario would be viewed similarly to the first =
one, in that the perceived culpability would be with the user despite the f=
act almost the entire image is generated by AI.

Moreover, I think this perceived culpability would remain with the user no =
matter how high fidelity the AI becomes (i.e. a movie instead of an image);=
 yes, there may be more complaints on the margins, but any reasonable criti=
c would understand the user volition required to make our sordid image.

There are two analogies that explain why this is my expectation: first, 3D =
printers can be used to create guns, but in fact are used for making litera=
lly anything else ~99.99% of the time; reasonable people accept that bad pe=
ople will do bad things, but that is not worth banning the tool entirely. T=
he second analogy is even closer to home: the Internet itself. There are ob=
viously bad things that can happen when communities come together, but we h=
ave accepted as a society that the benefits of widespread connectivity outw=
eigh the fact said connectivity could be leveraged for evil ends.

*Scenario 3: A user enters the prompt =E2=80=9Ca bunny being tortured=E2=80=
=9D into Dall-E and gets an image of a bunny being tortured.*

I hope you bulked up your security, because the gate is being stormed in th=
e morning! Obviously this is the fault of AI: how dare you release such evi=
l upon the land?

I=E2=80=99m obviously being hyperbolic, but only to a point: the mistake co=
mpanies are making is completely removing user agency from the creation pro=
cess, which means the perceived culpability is completely with the AI. Yes,=
 the user is technically at fault because they are the one that entered the=
 prompt, but text-to-image represents a level of abstraction that is a step=
 change in perception.

My strong suspicion, as illustrated by the tortured bunny example, is that =
increasing the number of user actions shifts the perceived culpability from=
 the AI to the user.

To make another analogy, consider the jurisprudence around entrapment: if a=
 police officer hands out free heroin samples and then arrests the buyers i=
t is clear entrapment and ruled unjust. The legal concept undergirding entr=
apment is that a legitimate arrest requires =E2=80=9Cthe perpetrator=E2=80=
=99s natural disposition to commit the crime and not be induced by social p=
ressure=E2=80=9D ( Sherman vs United States ( https://supreme.justia.com/ca=
ses/federal/us/356/369/ ) provides a good example). However, that doesn=E2=
=80=99t mean entrapment can=E2=80=99t be legal: successful entrapment cases=
 rely on the criminal consistently choosing the illegal path of their own f=
ree will. The key criteria for a successful prosecution is the number of in=
dividual discrete unprompted actions.

If we apply this framework to AI, then perceived culpability moves from the=
 AI to the user when the user performs a number of discrete unprompted acti=
ons that establish it is his/her will to create the end product.

More speculatively, underlying the =E2=80=9Cnatural predisposition=E2=80=9D=
 concept relied on in entrapment is an idea of the amount of work done. Suc=
cessful entrapment cases appear to rely on the perpetrator having independe=
ntly done a lot of work or undertaken effort to commit the crime (cross-ref=
erencing this conceptually to the legal concept of =E2=80=9Cpremeditated=E2=
=80=9D also provide oblique support for this line of reasoning). Likewise, =
it is clear that we do not blame an undergraduate text in chemistry for fac=
ilitating bomb-making, even though it contains all the information required=
, even as we take down websites (or AIs!) that repackage the exact same inf=
ormation in a simple-to-digest format. It turns out that effort =E2=80=94 e=
ither on the part of the perpetrator or the facilitator =E2=80=94 matter in=
 our moral calculus around culpability.

In summary, there are two drivers of complicity: 1. User choice and 2. User=
 effort. As the total set of (1) and (2) increases, perceived culpability s=
hifts from the AI (and its creator) to the end user.

*Applying the Framework*

The practical application of this framework is that all AI tools (LLM, imag=
e-gen or others) need to ensure user complicity as they move from uncontrov=
ersial results to those that some sections of society might find unacceptab=
le. Essentially they need to make the user clearly CHOOSE settings that ena=
ble bad content and then the users need to WORK HARD to get those outcomes

It is beyond the scope of this document to brainstorm UI and workflow mocku=
ps, although that speaks to the key point: this isn=E2=80=99t a model probl=
em; it=E2=80=99s a product problem. Instead of relying solely on RLHF (with=
 all the drawbacks therein), the UI and flow of the product should require =
user complicity to make the results more controversial. If the user has had=
 to toggle many different settings, and now has a UI that, due to those tog=
gle changes, displays explicit warnings, then the perceived culpability is =
different. Indeed, one could go even further by making the user have to =E2=
=80=9Cwork at it=E2=80=9D by requiring complex commands or by explicitly se=
lecting one of multiple results that has an NSFW tag to get to their end go=
al.

Another solution would be to make the user perform a thin RLHF overlay on t=
he AI; the user might be prompted to answer a series of questions if they w=
ant access to less vanilla results that make it =E2=80=9Cmy AI=E2=80=9D. Ag=
ain, by involving the user the moral onus moves: if I can make the AI say s=
omething inappropriate it is a =E2=80=9Cgotcha=E2=80=9D I can post on socia=
l media (Gemini suffered from this). Conversely if it is My AI that I helpe=
d train (and visually branded as such), posting a screenshot of something i=
nappropriate says something about me and my choices; in this case induced s=
hame is an attractive product quality.

*Conclusion*

Attempting to set a particular boundary of safety is impossible given the h=
eterogeneous nature of nation states, societies and political groups within=
 those nation states and the fact that morality is dynamic (it changes ever=
y decade and the =E2=80=9Cpast is a foreign country=E2=80=9D). Moreover, th=
e risk is not one-sided: people will be upset no matter what rules you plac=
e on the model; the only question is what set of people. This is a signific=
ant business risk ( https://stratechery.com/2024/aggregators-ai-risk/?acces=
s_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZ=
SIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenA=
iOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZW=
NoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDI0L2FnZ3JlZ2F0b3JzLWFpLXJpc2svIl19LCJleHAiOjE3MTIyMzgwOTUsI=
mlhdCI6MTcwOTY0NjA5NSwiaXNzIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9hcGkucGFzc3BvcnQub25saW5lL29hdXRo=
Iiwic2NvcGUiOiJmZWVkOnJlYWQgYXJ0aWNsZTpyZWFkIGFzc2V0OnJlYWQgY2F0ZWdvcnk6cmV=
hZCBlbnRpdGxlbWVudHMiLCJzdWIiOiJSc2V1WUU4amdIZVBwV0pmMWZBYjRDIiwidXNlIjoiYW=
NjZXNzIn0.VD-z75I5kD2Rf3ymnbDlx9lRzE7COevp9NwWtGaavKlM6Aqv5PHfnV7r1Tvhwp9H7=
JZ8w321y0n4IwfA1x4HxnfJTLiYbp3fDXIbkp9wlleTmTg4ehnO5BAnurntMyGCHRtqUjScNPk6=
Hf26JKgek4MKaE-E_7zif2fIBgxg3_rWeYm_6kSu-Mh8DYGWE6wpuqoWmG0Nlr_6kJieO7wUcAT=
rAm5eitXRgY35UzGBbXqgSrzQstUsn0SFI-8sTWRIyI84fUPGFlm2Fi7mQd9SZGgefkgwbm-TS9=
7PR3chhCctx7jfurezkIjcpuizsYJFh04Bg59ZMr-Y9yR3tyWB0w ).

The correct framework is to move culpability onto the user via product desi=
gn decisions that means the user is not =E2=80=9Centrapped=E2=80=9D by the =
AI but can only move to more controversial results via the application of c=
hoice and effort.

My thanks to my anonymous friend! I think this is good advice, and not just=
 because no one wants bad PR. Overly constricting AI is like any other form=
 of censorship: sure, you may stop a lot of the bad stuff you don=E2=80=99t=
 want, but you will also stop good stuff, particularly new and innovative t=
hings that are outside the norm, and which represent some of the biggest po=
tential upsides of AI. It makes sense to me that the solution is not to tre=
at users like children, but let them make choices in a way that makes it cl=
ear to everyone that AI is a tool, not an oracle.

